May 2024

Introduction

Modeling behavior in games

Nash equilibrium: A good first pass, but …

  • Humans won’t (perfectly) best respond
  • Payoff-insensitive predictions
  • Trouble with estimation (using maximum likelihood & Bayes)
    • Strictly dominated actions
    • Actions played with zero probability in equilibrium

Another kind of equilibrium

Quantal Response Equilibrium (McKelvey and Palfrey 1995)

  • Players probabilistically best respond to beliefs
  • Beliefs are consistent with mixed strategies (as in Nash)

\[ \begin{aligned} \sigma_i&=q_i(\sigma,\lambda,\theta) \end{aligned} \]

where:

  • \(q_i\) is player \(i\)’s probabilistic best response function
  • \(\sigma_i\) is player \(i\)’s mixed strategy
  • \(\lambda\geq 0\) is a choice precision parameter
  • \(\theta\) contains other parameters in the model (risk-aversion, inequality-aversion etc)

What is a probabilitsic best response?

Nash best response: Players only play actions that yield their maximum possible utility

Probabilistic best response: Players play all actions in their action set, but are more likely to play actions that yield greater utility.

Some examples:

\[ \begin{aligned} \text{logit: } q_{i,a}(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)&=\frac{\exp(\lambda u_{i,a}(\sigma,\theta))}{\sum_j\exp(\lambda u_{i,j}(\sigma,\theta)) }\\ \text{power: } q_{i,a}(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)&=\frac{u_{i,a}(\sigma,\theta)^\lambda}{\sum_ju_{i,j}(\sigma,\theta)^\lambda} \end{aligned} \]

As \(\lambda\to\infty\) these approach best response functions

The quantal response equilibrium condition

\[ \sigma_i=q_i(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)\quad \forall i \]

A fixed point, just like Nash.

This brings with it some of the same problems associated with solving for Nash

Solving for Nash is a PPAD-complete problem (Daskalakis, Goldberg, and Papadimitriou 2009):

  • Generally thought to be difficult to solve
  • Very easy to verify if you have found a solution

What does QRE look like?

Example game: Asymmetric chicken (Goeree, Holt, and Palfrey 2016)

Asymmetric Chicken game
Left Right
Up 0, 0 6, 1
Down 1, 14 2, 2

\[ \begin{aligned} U_U(\sigma)&=6\sigma_R,\quad U_D(\sigma)=\sigma_L+2\sigma_R\\ U_L(\sigma)&=14\sigma_D, \quad U_R(\sigma)= \sigma_U+2\sigma_D \end{aligned} \]

For this example, I will use the logit probabilistic best response function:

\[ \begin{aligned} q_{i,a}(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)&=\frac{\exp(\lambda u_{i,a}(\sigma,\theta))}{\sum_j\exp(\lambda u_{i,j}(\sigma,\theta))} \end{aligned} \]

Existing methods for solving for QRE

\[ \sigma_i=q_i(\sigma,\lambda,\theta),\quad \forall i \]

Many and varied:

  • Hope that it is a contraction (no guarantee)
  • Minimize sum of squared errors (inefficient)
  • Predictor-corrector algorithm (Turocy 2010)
    • Start at a known solution \((\sigma,\lambda,\theta)\)
      • Can always start at the centroid: uniform randomization and \(\lambda = 0\)
    • Trace out a “path” or “branch” from here
    • This is what the software package Gambit (McKelvey, McLennan, and Turocy 2014) does

Predictor-corrector algorithm - overview

Starting point: A known solution to \(\sigma= q(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)\)

  • “Centroid” is always available to start: \(\lambda = 0\), \(\sigma_{i,a} = \frac{1}{A_i}\)

Predictor step: Propose a nearby solution based on a linear approximation of the system

  • Needs derivatives of the system

Corrector step:

  • Correct any errors associated with this approximation

More on the predictor-corrector algorithm

Define a system of equations that characterizes the QRE, e.g.

\[ \begin{aligned} 0&=\log \sigma_{i,a+1}-\log \sigma_{i,a}-\log q_{i,a+1}(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)+\log q_{i,a}(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)\\ 0&=1-\sum_{a=1}^{A_i}\sigma_{i,a} \end{aligned} \]

Call this \(0=G(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)\).

Then use \(\frac{\partial G(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)}{\partial \sigma^\top}\) and \(\frac{\partial G(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)}{\partial \lambda}\) to find a solution nearby.

  1. Predictor step: Use these derivatives to approximate the system linearly.
  2. Corrector step: correct any errors made with this approximation. Go back to Step 1.

See Bland and Turocy (2023) for a detailed description of how to implement this

When there is only one path, the predictor-corrector algorithm works well, but…

A simulation-based method of approximating QRE

  • Construct a distribution whose global modes are quantal response equilibria
  • Sample from this distribution

Estimation using Bayesian techniques

An approximation through simulation

What this will rely on

We can sample mixed strategy profiles \(\sigma\mid \lambda,\theta\) from distributions that we specify in the following form:

\[ \log p(\sigma\mid \lambda,\theta)=g(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)+c(\lambda,\theta) \]

where:

  • \(g(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)\) is a function that we choose, and
  • \(c(\lambda,\theta)\) is a normalizing constant.
    • We don’t need to know this part!

This is exactly the way probabilistic programming languages like Stan (Carpenter et al. 2017) accept information about probability distributions!

Using the QRE condition

We can write the QRE condition like this:

\[ \begin{aligned} 0&=H_{i,a}(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)\doteq\sigma_{i,a}-q_{i,a}(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)\\ &\forall i\in 1, 2, \ldots n,\quad \forall a \in 1, 2, \ldots, A_i \end{aligned} \]

Therefore for any positive definite weighting matrix \(W\):

\[ \begin{aligned} H(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)^\top WH(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)=0&\iff (\sigma,\lambda,\theta)\text{ is a QRE}\\ H(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)^\top WH(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)>0&\iff (\sigma,\lambda,\theta)\text{ is not a QRE}\\ \end{aligned} \]

Putting this into a distribution

\[ \log p(\sigma\mid \lambda,\theta)=-H(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)^\top WH(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)+c(\lambda,\theta) \]

Given \((\lambda,\theta)\):

  • Globally maximized wrt \(\sigma\) at any QRE \((\sigma,\lambda,\theta)\).
  • Less probability density elsewhere

The distribution will have modes of all the QRE for fixed \((\lambda,\theta)\)

Practical implications:

  • If we sample \(\sigma\) from this distribution, draws will likely be close to a QRE.
  • We can make draws arbitrarily close in probability by increasing \(W\).

Diagnosing multiple equilibria

\[ \text{multiuple equilibria} \iff \text{multiple modes} \]

Run more than one Monte Carlo chain with different starting values

  • Convergence diagnostics
  • Gelman-Rubin statistic \(\hat R\) (Gelman and Rubin 1992)

Tracing out the QRE locus

Instead of fixing \(\lambda\), assign it a prior:

\[ \log p(\sigma,\lambda\mid \theta)=-H(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)^\top WH(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)+\log p(\lambda \mid \theta) + c(\theta) \]

Sampler now explores the locus of QRE

Using a Metropolis-Hastings sampler

Implementation in Stan

\[ \log\lambda \sim N(\log0.1,0.7^2) \]

Estimation

Combining the distribution with a prior

\[ \begin{aligned} p(\sigma,\lambda,\theta\mid y)&\propto p(y\mid \sigma,\lambda,\theta)p(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)\\ &=p(y\mid \sigma,\lambda,\theta)p(\sigma\mid \lambda,\theta)p(\lambda,\theta)\\ \log p(\sigma,\lambda,\theta\mid y)&=y^\top \log \sigma-H(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)^\top WH(\sigma,\lambda,\theta)+\log p(\lambda,\theta)+c \end{aligned} \]

where \(y\) are action counts

Estimation

  • \(\log \lambda \sim N(\log 0.1,0.7^2)\)
  • 100 decisions per dataset
  • Difficulty finding solutions on the non-principal branch: prior issues

Conclusion

A simulation-based approach for computing and estimating QRE

Construct a distribution whose modes are QRE

Sample from this distribution

Tracing the locus: use a prior for \(\lambda\)

Estimating models: use a prior for \(\lambda\) and add the likelihood

Comparison to the predictor-corrector algorithm

Predictor-corrector

  • Exact solution needed initially for each branch

  • Needs derivatives

  • Distinction between principal and non-principal branches

  • Estimation easy (if on the principal branch). MLE or Bayesian

Simulation

  • Need a solution close enough to QRE to find it
  • No need for derivatives\(^*\)
  • No distinction between principal and non-principal branches
  • Estimation easy (if not worried about principal branch). Need Bayesian approach

Should I consider using this?

No, if the predictor-corrector algorithm or something else works well for you.

  • More computationally intensive (but maybe less user intensive)

No, if you want to focus on the principal branch and you know there are other branches

Yes, if you want to estimate or compute a QRE with multiple branches and you don’t want to make the distinction between the principal branch and others

Yes, when other techniques struggle

Are there any more examples?

  • Generalized matching pennies with and without risk aversion (Selten and Chmura 2008)
  • Volunteer’s Dilemma with heterogeneous preferences (Goeree, Holt, and Smith 2017)
  • First-price private-value auction with risk-averse bidders (simulated data)
